But the most abstract end of it for our purposes is the

66
00:02:38,452 --> 00:02:42,622
Poisson formulation of classical mechanics based on the idea of Poisson brackets.

67
00:02:44,702 --> 00:02:46,942
What Poisson brackets do,

68
00:02:46,942 --> 00:02:50,402
or what they're useful for,

69
00:02:50,402 --> 00:02:53,782
is describing flows on phase space.

70
00:02:55,582 --> 00:02:57,982
One kind of flow on phase space is

71
00:02:57,982 --> 00:03:00,382
the motion of the phase space with time,

72
00:03:00,382 --> 00:03:02,102
or the motion of the

73
00:03:02,102 --> 00:03:03,822
points in phase space with time.

74
00:03:04,501 --> 00:03:07,821
How the actual points evolve with time

75
00:03:07,821 --> 00:03:11,142
under the influence of a particular Hamiltonian.

76
00:03:11,582 --> 00:03:14,022
That's one kind of flow on phase space.

77
00:03:14,402 --> 00:03:17,372
But there are other kinds of flows on phase

78
00:03:17,372 --> 00:03:20,342
space that you can imagine with possibly somewhat different purposes.

79
00:03:21,382 --> 00:03:22,422
For example,

80
00:03:22,422 --> 00:03:25,342
we can talk about symmetries.

81
00:03:25,822 --> 00:03:27,522
Now we've talked about symmetries.

82
00:03:27,602 --> 00:03:28,362
The basic symmetry,

83
00:03:28,362 --> 00:03:30,282
the problem for me in explaining symmetries

84
00:03:30,282 --> 00:03:32,202
is not that it's hard to explain.

85
00:03:32,502 --> 00:03:34,262
It's that there aren't too many symmetries.

86
00:03:34,262 --> 00:03:37,512
There are too many examples in classical mechanics that

87
00:03:37,512 --> 00:03:40,762
allow you a wide range of different situations to describe.

88
00:03:41,002 --> 00:03:44,652
The basic symmetries of most classical mechanical

89
00:03:44,652 --> 00:03:48,302
systems are rotations about various axes and translations.

90
00:03:51,361 --> 00:03:56,221
Special systems with particularly simple mathematics sometimes have

91
00:03:56,221 --> 00:04:01,082
some hidden symmetries that you might not have expected.

92
00:04:01,462 --> 00:04:03,622
But the basic symmetries are just those.

93
00:04:03,622 --> 00:04:04,722
The motions of space,

94
00:04:04,722 --> 00:04:05,302
translation,

95
00:04:05,302 --> 00:04:05,762
rotation.

96
00:04:06,502 --> 00:04:08,882
As you move on to more advanced physics,

97
00:04:08,882 --> 00:04:10,402
you discover more symmetries,

98
00:04:10,402 --> 00:04:11,702
different kinds of symmetries,

99
00:04:11,702 --> 00:04:13,862
symmetries among element-t particles and so forth.

100
00:04:14,102 --> 00:04:15,862
But those are not for us now.

101
00:04:19,442 --> 00:04:22,082
What do those symmetries have to do with flows?

102
00:04:22,942 --> 00:04:24,282
Flows in phase space.

103
00:04:24,562 --> 00:04:24,682
Well,

104
00:04:24,682 --> 00:04:27,702
let me begin with flows in just coordinate space.

105
00:04:28,302 --> 00:04:29,142
X-space.

106
00:04:29,962 --> 00:04:31,642
We can think of a rotation.

107
00:04:31,802 --> 00:04:33,522
We can think of rotations in space.

108
00:04:33,622 --> 00:04:36,462
As defining a kind of flow in the space.

109
00:04:36,642 --> 00:04:39,222
Just imagine going from here to here.

110
00:04:39,962 --> 00:04:41,762
Rotating our coordinates in space.

111
00:04:42,222 --> 00:04:44,252
By imagining an infinite

112
00:04:44,252 --> 00:04:46,282
number of intermediate configurations.

113
00:04:47,322 --> 00:04:50,162
And imagine in your head going from

114
00:04:50,162 --> 00:04:53,002
one configuration to another configuration of the axes.

115
00:04:53,122 --> 00:04:55,142
Of the axes of the space continuously.

116
00:04:56,822 --> 00:04:59,922
Or we don't have to imagine motion of the axes.

117
00:05:00,102 --> 00:05:02,782
We can actually imagine motion of a system.

118
00:05:02,782 --> 00:05:04,942
Where we rotate the whole system.

119
00:05:05,002 --> 00:05:06,262
We keep the axes fixed.

120
00:05:06,482 --> 00:05:08,402
And rotate the whole room.

121
00:05:09,682 --> 00:05:12,702
That rotation might not have anything to do

122
00:05:12,702 --> 00:05:15,722
with the actual time dependence of the system.

123
00:05:15,902 --> 00:05:17,872
It simply allows us to

124
00:05:17,872 --> 00:05:19,842
describe mathematically what a rotation is.

125
00:05:20,022 --> 00:05:22,432
A rotation is something which is built

126
00:05:22,432 --> 00:05:24,842
up out of lots of little rotations basically.

127
00:05:26,002 --> 00:05:28,412
And so we can think of

128
00:05:28,412 --> 00:05:30,822
the idea of a coordinate transformation.

129
00:05:30,822 --> 00:05:32,932
Which rotates the coordinates of

130
00:05:32,932 --> 00:05:35,042
space as a kind of flow.

131
00:05:36,662 --> 00:05:38,842
Likewise the translation of space.

132
00:05:39,182 --> 00:05:42,502
The motion from one point moving our coordinate axes.

133
00:05:42,562 --> 00:05:43,562
Not rotating them.

134
00:05:43,722 --> 00:05:45,162
But translating them.

135
00:05:45,402 --> 00:05:48,202
We can also think of that as being built up.

136
00:05:49,142 --> 00:05:51,212
A given translation as being built

137
00:05:51,212 --> 00:05:53,282
up by a lot of little translations.

138
00:05:53,422 --> 00:05:54,682
Which define a flow.

139
00:05:55,342 --> 00:05:57,522
It's those flows in phase space.

140
00:05:57,702 --> 00:05:59,162
Not just in coordinate space.

141
00:05:59,162 --> 00:06:01,222
But transformations which mix together

142
00:06:01,222 --> 00:06:03,282
or potentially could mix together.

143
00:06:03,622 --> 00:06:05,562
Both the P's and the Q's.

144
00:06:05,762 --> 00:06:07,442
Into a richer structure.

145
00:06:07,942 --> 00:06:11,622
Than just the transformations which mix up the coordinates.

146
00:06:12,142 --> 00:06:15,962
I use coordinates to mean Q's or X's.

147
00:06:16,242 --> 00:06:18,352
I use phase space to talk

148
00:06:18,352 --> 00:06:20,462
about the P's and the Q's.

149
00:06:21,722 --> 00:06:24,762
We can become interested and we will become interested.

150
00:06:24,982 --> 00:06:27,442
In transformations which mix the P's and Q's.

151
00:06:27,642 --> 00:06:29,142
And so it's a richer flow.

152
00:06:29,162 --> 00:06:32,122
A family of transformations that we can imagine.

153
00:06:32,742 --> 00:06:34,782
And those flows which move things

154
00:06:34,782 --> 00:06:36,822
around in phase space in various ways.

155
00:06:36,942 --> 00:06:40,442
Are described by the method of Poisson brackets.

156
00:06:41,982 --> 00:06:44,962
So I try to make it a

157
00:06:44,962 --> 00:06:47,942
habit of not beginning in the middle.

158
00:06:48,442 --> 00:06:50,262
Even though I may have covered

159
00:06:50,262 --> 00:06:52,082
something fairly completely in the previous lecture.

160
00:06:52,502 --> 00:06:53,922
So I like to go back over.

161
00:06:54,122 --> 00:06:55,592
Even if it means I

162
00:06:55,592 --> 00:06:57,062
do it two or three times.

163
00:06:58,162 --> 00:06:59,142
Let's just read through.

164
00:06:59,162 --> 00:07:01,062
And review what we know about Poisson brackets.

165
00:07:02,562 --> 00:07:05,562
But let's be French mathematicians.

166
00:07:05,622 --> 00:07:06,342
Let's abstract.

167
00:07:06,862 --> 00:07:09,452
Rather than write down the

168
00:07:09,452 --> 00:07:12,042
concrete definition of a Poisson bracket.

169
00:07:12,682 --> 00:07:16,082
Let's think about it from a more abstract

170
00:07:16,082 --> 00:07:19,482
collection of postulates or axioms about Poisson brackets.

171
00:07:20,882 --> 00:07:22,482
The Poisson brackets.

172
00:07:24,462 --> 00:07:25,202
Between.

173
00:07:25,602 --> 00:07:27,742
What are Poisson brackets.

174
00:07:27,982 --> 00:07:29,142
What go into the Poisson brackets.

175
00:07:29,162 --> 00:07:30,982
A thing that I'll call A

176
00:07:30,982 --> 00:07:32,802
and a thing that I'll call B.

177
00:07:33,262 --> 00:07:35,582
Both A and B are imagined to

178
00:07:35,582 --> 00:07:37,902
be functions of the P's and Q's.

179
00:07:38,542 --> 00:07:42,752
So we can write Poisson bracket of A of

180
00:07:42,752 --> 00:07:46,962
P and Q with B of P and Q.

181
00:07:49,302 --> 00:07:51,232
First of all has the

182
00:07:51,232 --> 00:07:53,162
abstract property that it's anti-symmetric.

183
00:07:53,782 --> 00:07:56,032
Anti-symmetric means that it changes sign

184
00:07:56,032 --> 00:07:58,282
if you interchange A and B.

185
00:08:05,502 --> 00:08:07,182
That's the first abstract property.

186
00:08:09,862 --> 00:08:10,322
Oops.

187
00:08:10,322 --> 00:08:11,202
Minus sign.

188
00:08:11,202 --> 00:08:11,782
Thank you.

189
00:08:12,342 --> 00:08:13,462
Most important thing.

190
00:08:13,462 --> 00:08:14,102
The minus sign.

191
00:08:16,222 --> 00:08:16,682
Right.

192
00:08:16,682 --> 00:08:18,602
So that's abstract property number one.

193
00:08:19,222 --> 00:08:21,192
Abstract property number two I won't write

194
00:08:21,192 --> 00:08:23,162
down in detail unless you ask me to.

195
00:08:23,762 --> 00:08:25,082
It's the linearity.

196
00:08:25,742 --> 00:08:26,982
Oh let me write it down.

197
00:08:30,342 --> 00:08:33,602
Supposing we have the Poisson bracket

198
00:08:33,602 --> 00:08:36,861
of some combination of A and B.

199
00:08:37,722 --> 00:08:39,402
Let's say alpha A,

200
00:08:39,402 --> 00:08:40,902
alpha and beta are numbers.

201
00:08:41,202 --> 00:08:42,241
Any numbers.

202
00:08:42,741 --> 00:08:49,232
Alpha A plus beta B Poisson bracket with C is just

203
00:08:49,232 --> 00:08:55,722
equal to alpha times the Poisson bracket of A with C.

204
00:08:58,162 --> 00:09:03,082
Plus beta times the Poisson bracket of B with C.

205
00:09:10,102 --> 00:09:12,502
So that's the property of linearity.

206
00:09:12,542 --> 00:09:13,742
This is anti-symmetry.

207
00:09:18,242 --> 00:09:19,822
This is linearity.

208
00:09:24,482 --> 00:09:25,702
Then there's the product.

209
00:09:25,702 --> 00:09:25,962
Product rule.

210
00:09:26,602 --> 00:09:28,822
What kinds of things are the A's and the B's?

211
00:09:29,402 --> 00:09:30,042
Capital A.

212
00:09:30,042 --> 00:09:30,722
What kind of what?

213
00:09:30,982 --> 00:09:31,982
Things are the A's.

214
00:09:32,322 --> 00:09:32,762
Functions.

215
00:09:32,762 --> 00:09:34,562
Functions of P's and Q's.

216
00:09:34,802 --> 00:09:36,162
P squared plus Q squared.

217
00:09:36,162 --> 00:09:37,102
Sine of P.

218
00:09:37,102 --> 00:09:37,522
Whatever.

219
00:09:37,862 --> 00:09:38,442
Is it real value?

220
00:09:39,002 --> 00:09:39,762
Not necessarily.

221
00:09:40,862 --> 00:09:41,822
But you can add it.

222
00:09:42,662 --> 00:09:44,932
There's no reason why in these formulas you

223
00:09:44,932 --> 00:09:47,202
can't take alpha and beta to be complex numbers.

224
00:09:47,822 --> 00:09:49,342
But you can't add A's and B's.

225
00:09:49,342 --> 00:09:49,942
That's all it says.

226
00:09:50,062 --> 00:09:50,722
You can add A's.

227
00:09:50,722 --> 00:09:51,001
Oh yes.

228
00:09:51,001 --> 00:09:52,021
You can add A's and B's.

229
00:09:52,021 --> 00:09:52,381
Absolutely.

230
00:09:52,702 --> 00:09:54,202
You can add A's and B's.

231
00:09:54,202 --> 00:09:55,602
Just adding the functions.

232
00:09:55,882 --> 00:09:56,222
Yeah.

233
00:09:56,942 --> 00:09:58,502
You can certainly add A's and B's.

234
00:09:59,402 --> 00:10:00,502
They're just functions.

235
00:10:03,302 --> 00:10:06,082
In classical mechanics there isn't much reason

236
00:10:06,082 --> 00:10:08,862
to be thinking about complex valued functions.

237
00:10:09,222 --> 00:10:11,082
But there's no reason that you can't.

238
00:10:11,262 --> 00:10:12,662
And sometimes you do.

239
00:10:12,802 --> 00:10:13,722
Sometimes you do.

240
00:10:13,802 --> 00:10:14,602
Sometimes it's useful.

241
00:10:14,782 --> 00:10:16,852
So they're just general functions

242
00:10:16,852 --> 00:10:18,922
of the coordinates of momenta.

243
00:10:19,062 --> 00:10:21,502
Remember the coordinates when I write down P's and

244
00:10:21,502 --> 00:10:23,942
Q's I don't just mean one P and one Q.

245
00:10:24,202 --> 00:10:27,012
I mean N P's and N Q's where

246
00:10:27,012 --> 00:10:29,822
N is the number of coordinates of the system.

247
00:10:31,422 --> 00:10:32,022
Okay.

248
00:10:32,022 --> 00:10:33,362
So that's the linearity.

249
00:10:34,122 --> 00:10:35,722
Then there's the product rule.

250
00:10:38,762 --> 00:10:45,142
The Poisson bracket of A times B with C is

251
00:10:45,142 --> 00:10:51,522
equal to A times the Poisson bracket of B with C.

252
00:10:59,222 --> 00:11:00,262
Plus B.

253
00:11:04,642 --> 00:11:05,162
A.

254
00:11:05,602 --> 00:11:05,602
A.

255
00:11:05,602 --> 00:11:09,082
Thank you.

256
00:11:12,102 --> 00:11:12,622
B.

257
00:11:14,682 --> 00:11:18,062
Now I've written these formulas in a particular order here.

258
00:11:18,402 --> 00:11:20,262
I've left the A on the left

259
00:11:20,262 --> 00:11:22,122
here and the B on the right.

260
00:11:22,422 --> 00:11:23,782
There's no reason for that.

261
00:11:23,782 --> 00:11:25,122
These are just numbers.

262
00:11:25,342 --> 00:11:26,882
That is to say they're

263
00:11:26,882 --> 00:11:28,422
functions whose values are just numbers.

264
00:11:28,802 --> 00:11:33,432
And it doesn't matter whether you multiply A times

265
00:11:33,432 --> 00:11:38,062
the Poisson bracket or the Poisson bracket times A.

266
00:11:39,062 --> 00:11:41,472
Mathematically speaking these things all commute which

267
00:11:41,472 --> 00:11:43,882
means you can multiply them in any order.

268
00:11:44,822 --> 00:11:49,042
I've written it in a form which won't mean anything to you

269
00:11:49,042 --> 00:11:53,262
now but it will mean next quarter when we study quantum mechanics.

270
00:11:53,262 --> 00:11:55,582
In quantum mechanics things don't commute.

271
00:11:55,762 --> 00:11:57,762
And I've written in a particular order

272
00:11:57,762 --> 00:11:59,762
which is still correct in quantum mechanics.

273
00:12:00,042 --> 00:12:04,482
But for our purposes now A times the Poisson bracket of B and

274
00:12:04,482 --> 00:12:08,922
C is just nothing but the Poisson bracket of B and C times A.

275
00:12:09,122 --> 00:12:11,312
So it doesn't matter whether the B's

276
00:12:11,312 --> 00:12:13,502
come first or the Poisson brackets come first.

277
00:12:13,682 --> 00:12:15,362
It does matter the order that

278
00:12:15,362 --> 00:12:17,042
you write down the Poisson bracket itself.

279
00:12:18,482 --> 00:12:20,282
